The paper deals with the problem of non-adaptive group testing with noise, which is a well-studied problem in information theory (cs.IT) and data structures (cs.DS). The dilution effect, which is the focus of this paper, is a common phenomenon in biological screening, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfields of data mining (cs.DM) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper proposes efficient decoding schemes, which may be of interest to the subfield of computational complexity (cs.CC).
